The later part of the 20th century was so sci-fi. You had moon landings, people constantly going into space. You would 100% assume there would at least be a huge moon base by now. Must have been a huge disappointment for 60s era space enthusiasts who lived to see the 21st century

It seems everyone in the 70s just reasonably assumed a sci-fi future was all but inevitable and expected to see spaceships, Mars colonization, flights to other galaxies, etc. soon. In many ways currently the world seems far less futuristic in comparison. None of it came to be.

In a way the conspiracy take that the Moon landing was fake is more optimistic, as it preserves the possibility that progress is linear. We are just a bit behind where we think we are. The date H.G. Wells gave for the first manned flight around the moon (with no landing) was 2036

Imagine if suddenly in the 2030s you have some not that exciting news of some new manned flight around the moon and return, then in a couple years a moon landing (maybe by China, but with some Western astronauts on board) and this time progress just slowly continues and ramps up.
I would like to see it too, but it's probably going to take a few more centuries for it to become like in the books

Totally demolished someone in an argument about red wine being "more aristocratic" than white wine. Multiple examples including members of the British royal family, Bourbons, and Napoleon III. I don't even prefer white wine, but red wine supremacists get way ahead of themselves.

Napoleon III's favorite was Riesling from Alsace for the record. Wine tastes better if it comes from a region with no legal separation of church and state. Alsace-Lorraine is also the area that Jack London predicted a world war would start over one day.

I posted about how my mother lost her Virgin Mary medallion as it fell from her necklace (found it later), but interestingly when she took it to the jeweler, they said both the necklace and medallion were whole even though the metal had thinned, had no idea how it had fallen off.
For the record I don't think it's anything paranormal or spiritual, just some weird natural property of metal. Jewelry is weird like that.

I think I explained it in a retarded way. Imagine two rings in a chain. There's no way to separate them without breaking one. Then imagine you see the two rings separated and one is thinner and worn out but there is no actual hole, its integrity is preserved. How could it happen?
